    {
      "id": "b1906b5e1696fe77de2a06ec780f5b2e46c66d9c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-21 18:50:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nNote that there is already \"lctl memhog\" that could be used for memory usage, without adding yet another binary for testing.\n\nI'm not sure it really belongs to lctl though, maybe multiop (our testing Swiss Army knife) would be a better place?  IIRC there may be a few memhog users in the test scripts, if this is changed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3683792fb3790b8b54658393d80834d9106ec282",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 257,
        "name": "Keith Mannthey",
        "email": "keith.mannthey@intel.com",
        "username": "kmannth",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-11-21 21:00:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI looked at memhog a little and it didn't seem ideal.  Right now is seem to be a \"Tell me how much memory you want me to eat\" program.  The issue with that is as you approach but not cross over the OOM threshold in the time it takes to allocate the memory the Target amount can change and you can wind up crossing into OOM.  Putting a box into OOM is not really useful,  making allocation requests block a bit more than normal is.   Exhausting swap can take a while and the system is live.  \n\nThe basic code for both of these could can be easily factored,  Perhaps making memhog to have a safe eat everything mode would be good. \n\n\"memhog -a\" for automatic perhaps. How about memhog -a runs an endless allocation/deallocation loop. ctrl -c kill it?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "704971c72c2bf87f397827411f6d90e6d452fedb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-22 01:42:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nKeith, if memhog doesn't have the features you are looking for, I'd much rather improve that tool than create a new one and have to maintain and install them both.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
